{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}} {{Infobox officeholder | honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]] | name = The Viscount Bracken | honorific-suffix = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] | image = Brendan Bracken 1947.jpg | imagesize = 250px | caption = Brendan Bracken in 1947 | order1 = [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]] | term_start1 = 25 May 1945 | term_end1 = 26 July 1945 | monarch1 = [[George VI of the United Kingdom|George VI]] | primeminister1 = [[Winston Churchill]] | predecessor1 = [[A. V. Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Hillsborough|A. V. Alexander]] | successor1 = A. V. Alexander | order2 = [[Ministry of Information (United Kingdom)|Minister of Information]] | term_start2 = 20 July 1941 | term_end2 = 25 May 1945 | primeminister2 = Winston Churchill | predecessor2 = [[Duff Cooper]] | successor2 = [[Geoffrey Lloyd, Baron Geoffrey-Lloyd|Geoffrey Lloyd]] | office3 = [[Parliamentary Private Secretary to the Prime Minister]] | term_start3 = 1940 | term_end3 = 1941 | primeminister3 = Winston Churchill | predecessor3 = [[Alec Douglas-Home|Lord Dunglass]] | successor3 = [[George Harvie-Watt]] | birth_date = {{birth-date|15 February 1901}} | birth_place = [[Templemore]], [[County Tipperary]], [[Ireland]] | death_date = {{death-date and age|8 August 1958|15 February 1901}} | death_place = | nationality = [[United Kingdom]] <!-- born when Ireland was still in UK; never held an Irish passport; named to British peerage as viscount --> | party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] }}
'''Brendan Rendall Bracken, 1st Viscount Bracken''', [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] (15 February 1901 – 8 August 1958) was an [[Irish people|Irish]]-born businessman and a [[Minister of the Crown|minister]] in the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] cabinet. He is best remembered for opposing the [[Bank of England|Bank of England's]] co-operation with [[Adolf Hitler]],<ref>{{YouTube|YauM5dHLn1s|Banking With Hitler}}, ''BBC'', 16 February 2006. Retrieved 31 July 2011</ref> and for subsequently supporting [[Winston Churchill]]'s prosecution of [[World War II]] against Hitler. He was also the founder of the modern version of the ''[[Financial Times]]''.<ref name=Lysaght/> He served as [[Ministry of Information (United Kingdom)|Minister of Information]] from 1941 to 1945.
==Early life== Brendan Rendall Bracken was born in [[Templemore]], [[County Tipperary]], [[Ireland]], the second son and third of the four children of [[Joseph Kevin Bracken]] (1852–1904), builder and monumental mason, and his second wife, Hannah Agnes Ryan (1872–1928). His father had belonged to the [[Irish Republican Brotherhood|IRB]] and was one of the seven founders of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]].{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}
Widowed in 1904, by 1908 Hannah Bracken had moved her family (including two stepdaughters) to [[Dublin]], where Brendan attended St Patrick's National School, [[Drumcondra, Dublin|Drumcondra]], until 1910, when he was transferred to the [[O'Connell School]], run by the [[Irish Christian Brothers]]. Distressed by his misbehaviour, his mother sent him in 1915 to [[Mungret College]], a [[Jesuit]] boarding school in [[County Limerick]], but he bolted in 1915 and ran up hotel bills. She then sent him to [[Australia]] to live with a cousin who was a priest in [[Echuca]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]. The young man led a nomadic existence in Australia, moving often but reading avidly and acquiring a self-education.<ref name=ODNB>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/printable/32020 Bracken profile at Oxford DNB]; accessed 26 February 2014.</ref>
In 1919 Bracken returned briefly to Ireland, finding his mother settled in [[County Meath]]. He distanced himself from Ireland and his siblings who were in revolt over their father's inheritance, moving instead to settle in [[Liverpool]]. In 1920 he appeared at [[Sedbergh School]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], claiming to be 15 years old, an [[Australian people|Australian]], to have been orphaned in a bush fire, and to have a family connection to Montagu Rendell, the then-headmaster of [[Winchester College]]. Without fully believing this story, Sedbergh's headmaster, impressed by the depth of knowledge and eagerness to progress by the young Bracken, accepted him. By the end of one term he emerged having succeeded in blending his [[Irish republican]] heritage and his five formative years in Australia, with the elements and trappings of a [[British public school]] man. He might have had good reason for seeking to hide his Irish heritage as the [[Irish War of Independence|War of Independence]] (1919–1921) aroused great hostility towards the [[Irish people|Irish]] living in [[Great Britain]].
For whatever reason this denial became a regular feature of his personal strategy in life. A second example occurred in 1926 when he met [[Major-General]] [[Emmet Dalton]], a former senior commander in the new [[Irish Army]], in [[London]]. This former [[British Army]] officer turned IRA confidant, who was one of [[General officer|General]] [[Michael Collins (Irish leader)|Michael Collins]]'s right-hand men, recalled meeting Bracken at [[National school (Ireland)|national school]] in Dublin. Bracken denied this, but Dalton insisted that he remembered the smell of Bracken's corduroy trousers. A third example occurred during the [[Second World War]] when Bracken told people that his brother had been killed in action at [[Battles of Narvik|Narvik]], when in fact his brother was alive, well, and asking Brendan for money, from Ireland. {{Citation needed|date=July 2012}}
==Business and political career== After Sedbergh, whose [[School tie#Old school tie|"old boy" tie]] he used to good effect, Bracken was briefly a schoolmaster at [[Bishop's Stortford College]]. He then made a successful career from 1922 as a magazine publisher and newspaper editor in [[London]]. His initial success was based on selling advertising space to at least cover the cost of each number. In the [[United Kingdom general election, 1923|1923 election]] he assisted [[Winston Churchill]]'s unsuccessful attempt to be elected as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Leicester West (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester West]], which started their political affiliation. He also assisted in the by-election at Westmister. In the fighting that occurred on the streets, Bracken was stabbed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sixty Minutes with Winston Churchill|author=[[W. H. Thompson]]|date=1964|orig-year=1953|publisher=Johnson Publications Ltd.|page=21}}</ref> Bracken himself stood for [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], being elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in 1929 for the London constituency of [[Paddington North (UK Parliament constituency)|North Paddington]]. [[Stanley Baldwin]] described Bracken as Churchill's "faithful chela", "chela" being the Hindi word for disciple.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.historytoday.com/charles-lysaght/churchills-faithful-chela |title=Charles Lysaght strips away some of the many mysteries surrounding Brendan Bracken, Churchill’s staunch but enigmatic supporter, and the founder of this magazine|journal=History Today|author= Lysaght, Charles |volume=52 |issue= 2|year=2002}}</ref>
Many of his early magazine stories included a political flavour and he commissioned articles from a wide range of politicians such as Churchill and [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]]. Business and politics permanently overlapped in his life, in a similar way to the career of his occasional friend [[Max Aitken, 1st Baron Beaverbrook|Lord Beaverbrook]]. He needed politicians for stories and they needed the publicity given by his publications. A supporter of Winston Churchill from 1923, when Churchill was out of Parliament and in the political wilderness, in the 1930s he was invited to join Churchill's "[[Other Club]]". Their lives changed from the outbreak of the [[Second World War]] in 1939.
In 1926, he was the founding editor of ''[[The Banker]]'' magazine and bankers still name their respected annual Bank of the Year awards "Brackens" in his honour.<ref>[http://www.thebanker.com/Awards/The-Bank-of-The-Year-Awards The Bank of the Year Awards"], ''The Banker''</ref> ''The Banker'' features a regular column called "Bracken",<ref>[http://www.thebanker.com/Comment/Bracken "The Bracken Column"] ''The Banker''</ref> focusing on providing views and perspectives on how to improve the [[global financial system]].
===Assists in selection of Churchill=== In two matters relating to Churchill, Bracken can be said to have played a key part behind the scenes. When [[Neville Chamberlain]] prepared to resign in May 1940, his successor would be Churchill or [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|Lord Halifax]]. The political issue at stake at the time was the formation of a British National Government, and the particular dilemma over which of Chamberlain's potential successors would be acceptable to the [[Labour Party (United Kingdom)|Labour Party]]. The view in Churchill's mind was that the Labour Party would not support him, and he had therefore agreed with Chamberlain to nominate Lord Halifax. When Bracken became aware of Churchill's agreement to nominate Lord Halifax, he convinced Churchill that the Labour Party would indeed support him as Chamberlain's successor, and that Lord Halifax's appointment would hand certain victory to Hitler. Bracken advised Churchill tactically to say nothing when the three met to arrange the succession. After a deafening silence during which Churchill was expected to nominate Halifax, the latter obligingly ruled himself out and Churchill was put forward as Britain's wartime Prime Minister, having avoided any appearance of disloyalty to Chamberlain.<ref name=Lysaght>Lysaght, pp. 172–173</ref>
===Support from the US 1940–41=== When Churchill became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] in May 1940, Bracken helped in moving him into [[No. 10 Downing Street|Downing Street]]. Bracken was sworn into the [[His Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] in 1940, despite his lack of ministerial experience, and became Churchill's [[parliamentary private secretary]].
An insight into the nature of the relationship between Churchill and Bracken is found in Churchill's history of World War II. Churchill writes that he had received telegrams from Washington about [[Harry Hopkins]], "stating that he was the closest confidant and personal agent of the President. I therefore arranged that he should be met by Mr. Brendan Bracken on his arrival."<ref>Churchill, W. (2005) ''The Second World War'', Vol. 3, Ch. 2. Penguin Classics. {{ISBN|0141441747}}. pp. 22–23</ref> The suggestion was that Churchill had arranged, as is diplomatic custom, for Hopkins to be met by the person who was his closest counterpart in British government, and that Bracken often played the role of confidant and personal agent to Churchill. After Bracken met Hopkins' flight on 9 January 1941, Churchill and Hopkins forged a close association. According to [[Charles Lysaght|Lysaght's]] biography, Bracken and Hopkins had met in America in the late 1930s, and this personal tie helped speed the decision to assist Britain nearly a year before the US actually entered the war.<ref>Lysaght, pp. 183–184.</ref>
===Minister of Information=== In 1941, Bracken was promoted to the post of [[Ministry of Information (United Kingdom)|Minister of Information]] where he served until 1945.<ref>[http://www.life.com/image/53374558"Brendan Bracken Press Conference" 1943 photo], life.com; accessed 26 February 2014.</ref> At the same time he was one of the heads of the [[Political Warfare Executive]].
==Post-war years== In 1945, after the break-up of the wartime coalition, Bracken was briefly made [[List of the First Lords of the Admiralty|First Lord of the Admiralty]] in the [[Churchill caretaker ministry]], but lost the post in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1945|fall of the Churchill government]] to [[Clement Attlee]]'s Labour Party. He himself lost his North Paddington seat but soon returned to the Commons, as member of parliament for [[Bournemouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth]] in a November 1945 by-election. He was a relentless critic of the Labour Government's policy of [[nationalisation]] and the retreat from Empire.<ref>''Irish Times'', 9 August 2008</ref> At the 1950 general election he was returned for [[Bournemouth East and Christchurch (UK Parliament constituency)|Bournemouth East and Christchurch]], a seat he held until the [[United Kingdom general election, 1951|general election the following year]]. In early 1952 he was elevated to the peerage as '''Viscount Bracken''', of [[Christchurch, Dorset|Christchurch]] in the [[Hampshire|County of Southampton]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39435|date=8 January 1952|page=194}}</ref> but never used the title nor sat in the [[House of Lords]]. He retired from publishing in 1956.
His best-known business accomplishment was merging the ''[[Financial News (1884-1945)|Financial News]]'' into the ''[[Financial Times]]'' in 1945. The latter was published from [[Bracken House, London|Bracken House]], London, clad in pink stone to match the colour of the paper, just east of [[St. Paul's Cathedral]], which was remodelled in 1989. At this stage he was also publishing ''[[The Economist]]''. In 1951, with his love of history, he helped found ''[[History Today]]'' magazine.
==Death== Bracken died of [[esophageal cancer]] on 8 August 1958, aged 57, in London.<ref>His article in the ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (Volume 7, page 147) simply states his death cause as "throat cancer".</ref> Although raised a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], he refused the [[last rites]] of the Church despite efforts by his nephew, Rev Kevin Bracken, a Cistercian monk at [[Portglenone Abbey|Bethlehem Abbey]], [[Portglenone]], [[County Antrim]], to persuade him.
He was [[cremation|cremated]] without ceremony at [[Golders Green Crematorium]].<ref>Note cremation was formally banned by the Catholic Church until 1963, and until 1966 Catholic priests were forbidden to officiate at cremation services.</ref> His being unmarried, the viscountcy died with him.<ref name=ODNB />
==2010 and 2015 television documentaries== On 21 December 2010, [[RTÉ One]] broadcast an hour-long TV documentary about his life entitled ''Brendan Bracken – Churchill's Irishman''. The programme was made by [[Spain|Spanish]] production company, Marbella Productions, in association with [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]], and examined Bracken's life through photographs, interviews, rare archive footage and dramatic reconstructions, and told of his importance in the areas of British political and journalistic life, despite his attempt to hide from history by having all his papers burned after his death.{{Citation needed|date=February 2012}}
The 2015 television documentary ''Churchill's Secret Son'' is the 90 minute version of the previous documentary ''Churchill's Irishman'', updated by the producers including additional images, stories about Bracken's life and additional footage. The programme was telecast on Discovery UK's History Channel on Saturday, 24 January 2015 at 10 pm, as part of the British History week, and coincided with the 50th anniversary of Churchill's death in 1965.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}
